Answer: A [bystander](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bystander_(psychology)) is someone who is watching an event, but not participating in it.

\begin{blockquote}

[A] bystander is someone who is present during an emergency or a crime, but who does not act to help those in danger or prevent the crime.
\end{blockquote}

So a bystander is someone who is present, but who does not intervene.

Answer: In addition to the other answers, the term \em{bystander} also applies to people who are present but who don't really know what's going on.

The [Wikipedia page on the term](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bystander_(psychology)) says:

\begin{blockquote}

Bystanders are those who are present during an emergency or a crime, but who do not act to help those in danger or prevent the crime.
\end{blockquote}

But the same article also says:

\begin{blockquote}

Bystanders are also those who are present during an emergency or a crime, but who do not know what is going on, or who do not know how to help.
\end{blockquote}

And:

\begin{blockquote}

In the case of a crime, bystanders may also be those who know what is going on, but who do not intervene to help the victim or stop the criminal.
\end{blockquote}

So there is an overlap with the definition given by [Roger](https://english.stackexchange.com/a/412771/145377), but it is a more general definition that covers people who are present but who don't know what's going on.

